While computer science students are taught how search engines work, they are rarely trained to identify who they affect and assess potential harms. This work creates the opportunity for students to dive deep into the specific problem of misinformation in search engines, learn its short-term and long-term impacts, and connect various search engine techniques to the psychological process of becoming more or less misinformation-tolerant. Designed for first-year CS courses, this module bundles a short pre-lecture lesson, interactive lecture activities, and a project-based coding assignment to help students build a simple search engine and discuss the ethical tradeoffs of different search engine techniques. The module encourages reflection on how technical design choices shape fairness and responsibility in society. Our contribution is an integrated sequence that (1) establishes a simplified technical foundation for indexing and ranking in search engines, (2) maps software choices to ethical outcomes through the lenses of stakeholders with consideration of potential harms and the expectations of trust, and (3) invites students to reconsider the social role of search engines and learn about emerging U.S. legal implications for individuals and corporations regarding misinformation spread. The module is easy to integrate into CS1/CS2 courses seeking to teach responsible design.